@SG_OTHERFILE_readme/readme SGEXTN README
SGEXTN is 05524F's own C++ framework for application development with an emphasis on pure C++ code. Users of SGEXTN will only need to write C++ (and GLSL if you need custom shaders). There is also an emphasis on clean header files for fast clang-tidy passes and easy availability of the source code which is linked on every documentation page.
No compiled binaries are available for SGEXTN but it is very easy to build one yourself. See @SG_ML_L011006setting up SGEXTN#setup for more information. You need Qt, CMake and Qt Shader Tools to build SGEXTN.
When developing SGEXTN applications, you are strongly encouraged to use the Qt Creator IDE. Qt Creator has tooling that SGEXTN uses either builtin or easily available through the Qt Maintenance Tool. You are strongly recommended to use Git, GitHub, and clang-tidy when building your applications.
This version of SGEXTN is designed to work with Qt version 6.10.0, though anything at or above Qt 6.9.1 is likely fine.
SGEXTN uses Qt Quick and QRhi for rendering, however users do not need to care at all about QML, JavaScript, and any other such nonsense. There is also no need to care about Qt's macros, the Qt meta object system, or signal-slot. In fact, your application does not even need to link Qt unless to satisfy linker requirements, just keep the Qt DLLs in the same folder when deploying your application.
SGEXTN exposes private API, so as long as you know exactly what you are doing, you can extend SGEXTN by using its private API, or even linking to Qt libraries and using Qt features side by side with SGEXTN. For example building a custom @SG_FINDREP_WIDGET that uses your own QQuickItem is completely feasible. Note that doing this will require deep understanding of the source code, since private API is not documented.
If you came here from somewhere other than GitHub, here is the @SG_ML_L01102AGitHub repositoryhttps://github.com/InfinityIntegral/SGEXTN.
